<TITLE> Homes, crops damaged as Rashmi rages </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 27 (bdnews24.com)  The country experienced driving overnight rain as Cyclonic Storm Rashmi approached land, with coastal areas suffering damage to houses and crops due to severe winds, and many thousands taking cover in cyclone shelters through the night. Launch movements were halted on inland routes as Rashmi crossed the Khulna-Barisal coast Monday morning, bringing torrential rains and driving winds of 60-80km/h, said a special met office bulletin. Moving northeast, Rashmi weakened into a land depression over Faridpur, Madaripur, Chandpur, Dhaka and adjoining areas, heading further inland, the weather office said. The storm front began crossing the coast near Patharghata in the early hours of Monday, with Mongla seaport and adjoining coastal areas advised to hoist danger signal 7. As the storm weakened, moving inland, they were advised to lower the danger signal and hoist local cautionary signal 3. Chittagong and Cox's Bazar seaports were also advised to lower their earlier danger signal 6, and hoist cautionary signal 3. Chittagong port resumed operations from Monday morning. bdnews24.com Bhola correspondent said that heavy rainfalls twinned with gusty winds continued till the early morning, with intermittent rainfall after 10am. Two men were reported dead as the storm hit Bhola Sunday night, local officials said. Patuakahli saw driving rain with cold winds, with ferry movements on all inland routes cancelled, said bdnews24.com's correspondent in the district. Many people were seen to head for cyclone centres. In Barisal, strong winds caused damage to homes by, but there were no reports of casualties, said bdnews24.com's correspondent. Thousands took cover in cyclone shelters overnight. The storm damaged 30 percent Aman crops in Barisal, one agricultural officer estimated. bdnews24.com Chittagong correspondent said authorities allowed ship movement in the port after the danger signal was lowered to local cautionary signal 3. The district was experiencing sporadic rain since morning. Chandpur and Khulna correspondents said thousands of houses and trees were damaged by the storm. bdnews2
